List domain where C++ used not in embedded device.

C++ absolutely isn’t confined to embedded work—in fact, 
a large chunk of high-performance backend and infrastructure across industries runs on C++. 
If you want a mental model, think: **“any system where latency, throughput, or resource control matters”**.
Here are the main domains where C++ is used heavily **on servers / backend / non-embedded systems**:

---

## 1. High-Frequency Trading (HFT) & FinTech

This is one of the strongest C++ domains.

* Ultra-low latency trading systems
* Market data feed handlers
* Order matching engines
* Risk engines

Used by firms like:

* Jane Street
* Citadel
* Goldman Sachs

Why C++?

* Microsecond-level latency matters
* Fine control over memory and CPU

---

## 2. Backend Infrastructure / Distributed Systems

A lot of large-scale backend systems are written partly in C++.

Examples:

* RPC frameworks
* Load balancers
* Storage systems
* Messaging systems

Used in:

* Google (core systems, search infra)
* Meta (performance-critical backend)
* Amazon (parts of AWS infra)

Why C++?

* Handles massive scale efficiently
* Better performance than Java/Python in critical paths

---

## 3. Databases & Storage Engines

Many major databases are written in C++.

Examples:

* MySQL
* MongoDB
* RocksDB

Where C++ is used:

* Query execution engine
* Indexing
* Storage layer

---

## 4. Game Engines (Core Systems)

Even if games have UI, the **engine itself is heavy C++ backend logic**.

Examples:

* Unreal Engine
* Unity (core parts in C++)

Work includes:

* Physics engine
* Rendering pipeline
* Memory systems
* AI systems

---

## 5. Simulation Systems (Non-GUI / Headless)

This fits very well with your interest.

Examples:

* Aerospace simulations
* Financial simulations
* Traffic / logistics simulators

Used by:

* NASA
* Boeing

These often run:

* On servers
* Without GUI (CLI / data output)

---

## 6. Networking & Telecom Systems

C++ is widely used in high-performance networking.

Examples:

* Packet processing systems
* Routers / network controllers
* Telecom core systems

Related tools:

* DPDK
* PcapPlusPlus

---

## 7. Operating Systems & System Software

Not embedded—full systems.

Examples:

* Linux kernel (mostly C, but ecosystem uses C++)
* Windows (parts in C++)

Also:

* Compilers
* Runtime systems
* File systems

---

## 8. AI / ML Infrastructure (Not model training in Python)

While Python is popular, 
the **core engines are C++**.

Examples:

* TensorFlow
* PyTorch

C++ is used for:

* Execution engines
* Performance optimization
* GPU interfacing

---

## 9. Browser Engines & Rendering Systems

The engines behind browsers are C++.

Examples:

* Chromium
* Firefox

Work includes:

* HTML/CSS parsing
* Rendering engine
* JavaScript execution

---

## 10. CLI Tools & Developer Infrastructure

Pure console-based C++—this aligns strongly with your interest.

Examples:

* Build systems
* Compilers
* Debuggers

Tools:

* Clang
* CMake

